These difficulties had so increased with the growth of authoritative legal literature that it became imperatively necessary to discover some remedy. That which most immediately suggested itself was to lirnit the authority which this literature in general enjoyed to a moderate number of books, a plan which had already in its favour the rough

scheme of precedence which general practice had established among the works of the classical jurists. The writings of these five jurists had thus obtained a preponderance which naturally ex- tendcd itself from the schools to the tribunals. Yet among them there were a great many controversiea, and in this epoch neither thc emperor nor the parties to an action were likely to be satisfied with the rule which Gaius (i. 7) states on the authority of Hadrian, that where jurists of different vicws were cited the judge might adopt whichever of the conflicting views he pleased. ln order to obviate these difficulties, Constantine had (an. 321) deprived of all validity the notes of Ulpian and Paulus on Papinian, in which they had often found occasion to controvert his opinions. Α more complete remedy was provided by the so·called ‘law of Citations,' issued nn. 426 by the emperors Theodosius Il and Valentinian 111.
